[
  'title' => 'Behavioural Activation: The Science of Doing',
  'title_sw' => 'Uanzishaji wa Tabia: Sayansi ya Kutenda',
  'slug' => 'behavioural-activation',
  'category' => 'depression',
  'language' => 'en',
  'level' => 'beginner',
  'duration_minutes' => 12,
  'thumbnail_emoji' => '🚶',
  'is_premium' => 1,
  'is_published' => 1,
  'order' => 2,
  'summary' => 'Break the depression-inactivity spiral by scheduling small, meaningful activities even when you do not feel like it.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Vunja mzunguko wa unyogovu-kutofanya kwa kupanga shughuli ndogo zenye maana, hata usipohisi hivyo.',
  'content' => "## The depression trap\n\nWhen you are depressed, you lose motivation. So you do less. Doing less means fewer moments of reward, connection, or accomplishment. This deepens the depression, which kills motivation further. It is a spiral.\n\nBehavioural activation (BA) is the most evidence-backed treatment component for depression. The core insight: you do not wait to feel motivated to act. You act, and the motivation follows.\n\n## Why this works\n\nYour brain's reward system responds to activity and achievement, even small ones. When you do a meaningful activity, even reluctantly, you give your brain the signals it needs to start recovering. Every action, however small, is a vote cast against depression.\n\n## The two types of activities that help\n\n**Pleasure activities** include things that used to bring you enjoyment: a short walk, listening to a specific song, calling one person.\n\n**Mastery activities** create a sense of accomplishment: washing dishes, replying to one message you have been putting off, making your bed.\n\n## How to do it\n\n**Start small.** Depression makes everything feel impossible. A 3-minute walk is not pathetic, it is evidence that you can act against your mood.\n\n**Schedule, do not decide.** Depression will talk you out of anything if you leave it open. Write it down: 10am, walk to the gate and back. Treat it like a medical appointment.\n\n**Rate your mood before and after.** Use a 0 to 10 scale. Most people notice even a small improvement. This is data. It teaches your brain that action shifts mood.\n\n**Build gradually.** Once you have a few activities in a week that reliably shift your mood, add another. Do not try to fill your whole week on day one.",
  'content_sw' => "## Mtego wa unyogovu\n\nUnyogovu unapoua motisha yako, unafanya kidogo. Kufanya kidogo kunamaanisha furaha na mafanikio kidogo zaidi. Hii inazidisha unyogovu zaidi.\n\nUanzishaji wa tabia ni matibabu bora zaidi ya unyogovu. Wazo kuu: haufanyi kazi ukiwa umengojea motisha. Unafanya kazi, na motisha inakuja baadaye.\n\n## Jinsi ya kufanya\n\nAnza kwa shughuli ndogo, tembea dakika tatu, osha vyombo, piga simu mtu mmoja. Panga wakati wake badala ya kuamua wakati huo. Pima hali yako kabla na baada.",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Action precedes motivation in depression, you do not wait to feel ready.", "Both pleasure and mastery activities fight depression effectively.", "Start with activities that take 2 to 5 minutes, size does not matter, momentum does.", "Schedule activities like appointments, depression will cancel anything left flexible.", "Even a 1-point mood improvement after an activity is evidence worth tracking."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Hatua inakuja kabla ya motisha katika unyogovu.", "Anza na shughuli ndogo sana, dakika 2-5 inatosha.", "Panga shughuli kama miadi ya daktari."]),
],

[
  'title' => 'Challenging Negative Thought Patterns',
  'title_sw' => 'Kupinga Mifumo ya Mawazo Hasi',
  'slug' => 'challenging-negative-thoughts',
