  'order' => 3,
  'summary' => 'Identify the cognitive distortions depression produces and learn CBT techniques to reframe them.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Tambua upotofu wa mawazo unaozalishwa na unyogovu na ujifunze mbinu za CBT za kuyarekebisha.',
  'content' => "## Thoughts are not facts\n\nDepression creates predictable patterns of distorted thinking. These distortions feel completely true when you are in them. Learning to name them is the first step to losing their power over you.\n\n## The most common distortions in depression\n\n**All-or-nothing thinking**: I failed at one thing, so I am a complete failure. Reality check: almost nothing is all-or-nothing.\n\n**Catastrophising**: This problem will ruin everything forever. Reality check: what is the actual most likely outcome, not the worst imaginable?\n\n**Mind reading**: They think I am pathetic. Reality check: what evidence do you actually have for that?\n\n**Emotional reasoning**: I feel worthless, therefore I am worthless. Reality check: feelings are not measurements of reality.\n\n**Personalisation**: Everything went wrong because of me. Reality check: what other factors contributed?\n\n**Filtering**: You notice only what went wrong and screen out what went right.\n\n## The three-column technique\n\nWhen a painful thought arises, write three things:\n\n1. The automatic thought, exactly as it appeared\n2. The distortion, which pattern is this?\n3. The balanced response, what would a fair witness say?\n\nYou do not need to believe the balanced response immediately. Write it anyway. With repetition, it starts to feel more possible.\n\n## The friend test\n\nIf a close friend came to you with the same situation, what would you actually say to them? Most people are far kinder to others than to themselves. The friend test helps you access that kinder, more accurate voice.",
  'content_sw' => "## Mawazo si ukweli\n\nUnyogovu unazalisha mifumo ya kawaida ya mawazo ya upotofu. Kujifunza kuyataja ni hatua ya kwanza.\n\n## Upotofu wa kawaida\n\nFikira ya kila kitu au hakuna kitu, kutarajia mbaya zaidi, kusoma mawazo ya wengine, kuhisi kwa sababu unafikiri.\n\n## Mbinu ya safu tatu\n\nWaandike fikira ya moja kwa moja, aina ya upotofu, na jibu la usawa. Fanya hivi mara kwa mara.",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Depression produces predictable thought distortions. Learning to name them weakens them.", "The most common are: all-or-nothing, catastrophising, mind reading, emotional reasoning, personalisation, filtering.", "The three-column technique is the core CBT exercise for negative thoughts.", "You do not need to believe the balanced response immediately. Writing it still helps.", "The friend test reveals the kinder, more accurate voice you rarely use on yourself."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Unyogovu unazalisha upotofu wa mawazo unaotarajiwa.", "Jifunza kuyataja: yote au chochote, kutarajia mbaya, kusoma mawazo.", "Mbinu ya safu tatu inasaidia kurekebisha mawazo."]),
