[
  'title' => 'Understanding the Gambling Urge',
  'title_sw' => 'Kuelewa Hamu ya Kucheza Kamari',
  'slug' => 'understanding-the-gambling-urge',
  'category' => 'gambling',
  'language' => 'en',
  'level' => 'beginner',
  'duration_minutes' => 10,
  'thumbnail_emoji' => '🎰',
  'is_premium' => 1,
  'is_published' => 1,
  'order' => 1,
  'summary' => 'Understand what drives gambling urges at the neurological level and why willpower alone is not enough to stop them.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Elewa kinachosababisha hamu ya kucheza kamari kwa kiwango cha neva na kwa nini nguvu ya mapenzi peke yake haitoshi.',
  'content' => "## Problem gambling is not a moral failure\n\nProblem gambling is a recognised condition driven by the same brain mechanisms as other addictions. People from all backgrounds develop it. Understanding the biology does not remove your responsibility, but it does remove the shame, and shame is one of the biggest barriers to recovery.\n\n## What happens in your brain\n\nGambling hijacks the dopamine reward system. The specific mechanism is variable ratio reinforcement: gambling pays out on an unpredictable schedule. Not every time, not never, but sometimes, in a pattern you cannot predict. Neuroscience shows this is the most addictive pattern possible. Betting apps and casino games are deliberately designed around it.\n\n**Near misses**: when you almost win, your brain fires dopamine as if you had won. This is a loss your brain misregisters as almost-winning.\n\n**Anticipation is the driver**: dopamine peaks not when you receive a reward but when you anticipate one. This is why the experience of placing a bet feels compelling even before any result.\n\n## The loss-chasing trap\n\nAfter a loss, the brain registers a deficit and urges you to restore it. Chasing by continuing to bet to recover losses feels rational. It is not. Each bet is independent. The previous loss does not change the odds. Chasing escalates losses and is one of the most dangerous patterns in problem gambling.\n\n## The urge is not a command\n\nAn urge is a signal your brain sends, not an instruction you must obey. Urges have a shape: they build, peak, and pass. They typically last 15 to 30 minutes at their most intense. If you can outlast the urge without acting on it, it will pass.",
  'content_sw' => "## Kamari si kushindwa kwa maadili\n\nKamari ya tatizo ni hali inayotambuliwa inayoendeshwa na taratibu sawa za ubongo kama madawa mengine. Kuelewa biolojia haziondoi jukumu lako, lakini inaondoa aibu.\n\n## Kinachoendelea kwenye ubongo wako\n\nKamari inaibia mfumo wa tuzo wa dopamine. Variable ratio reinforcement ni mfumo unaolevya zaidi. Near misses zinasababisha ubongo kufanya kama umeshinda.",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Problem gambling is driven by brain mechanisms, it is not a moral failure.", "Variable ratio reinforcement (unpredictable payouts) is the most addictive pattern possible.", "Near misses fire dopamine as if you won. They are losses your brain misregisters.", "Dopamine peaks during anticipation. The urge to bet is itself the high.", "Urges build, peak, and pass in 15 to 30 minutes. You do not have to act on them."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Kamari ya tatizo ni tatizo la ubongo, si kushindwa kwa maadili.", "Variable ratio reinforcement ni mfumo unaolevya zaidi.", "Hamu zinajenga, kufikia kilele, na kupita ndani ya dakika 15-30."]),
],

[
  'title' => 'Identifying Your Gambling Triggers',
  'title_sw' => 'Kutambua Visababishi Vyako vya Kamari',
  'slug' => 'gambling-triggers',
  'category' => 'gambling',
  'language' => 'en',
  'level' => 'beginner',
  'duration_minutes' => 12,
  'thumbnail_emoji' => '🎯',
  'is_premium' => 1,
  'is_published' => 1,
  'order' => 2,
  'summary' => 'Map the people, places, emotions, and times that reliably trigger your gambling urges so you can plan around them.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Weka ramani ya watu, maeneo, hisia, na nyakati zinazosababisha hamu yako ya kucheza kamari ili uweze kupanga kuzunguka.',
  'content' => "## Why triggers matter\n\nRecovery from gambling does not happen through willpower in the moment. It happens through planning before the moment. If you know what triggers your urges, you can avoid high-risk situations, create barriers, and plan specific responses before you need them.\n\n## The four categories of triggers\n\n**External triggers** include places near a betting shop, technology such as apps on your phone and sports notifications, people you used to bet with, payday when money is available, and sport events.\n\n**Emotional triggers** include stress and anxiety, boredom, loneliness, excitement-seeking, low mood, and even celebration.\n\n**Thought triggers** include: I can control it this time, just one bet, I know this team will win, I am owed a win, no one will know.\n\n**Situational triggers** include unstructured time such as evenings and weekends, after a major stressor, and after even moderate alcohol use which lowers inhibitions.\n\n## Building your trigger map\n\nFor each trigger, write:\n1. The trigger as specifically as possible\n2. What you usually do, your typical response\n3. What you will do instead, a specific pre-planned alternative\n\n## The 15-minute rule\n\nFor any trigger that creates an urge, do anything else for 15 minutes. Call someone from your support network. Go for a walk. Make a meal. The urge will peak within that time and then decrease. You outlast it.",
  'content_sw' => "## Kwa nini visababishi ni muhimu\n\nKupona kutoka kwa kamari hakutokei kwa nguvu ya mapenzi wakati huo. Inatokea kwa kupanga kabla ya wakati huo.\n\n## Aina nne za visababishi\n\n- Vya nje: maeneo, teknolojia, watu, siku ya malipo\n- Vya kihisia: msongo, uchovu, upweke, kutafuta msisimko\n- Vya mawazo: ninaweza kudhibiti wakati huu, bet moja tu\n- Vya hali: wakati usiopangwa, baada ya stres kubwa",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Recovery happens through planning before urge moments, not willpower during them.", "Triggers fall into four categories: external, emotional, thought-based, and situational.", "Map your specific triggers and write a pre-planned alternative response for each.", "Technology triggers like apps and notifications should be removed permanently, not just managed.", "The 15-minute rule: do anything else for 15 minutes and the urge will peak and decrease."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Kupona kunatokea kwa kupanga kabla, si nguvu ya mapenzi wakati wa hamu.", "Visababishi vina aina nne: vya nje, vya kihisia, vya mawazo, vya hali.", "Sheria ya dakika 15: fanya kitu chochote kingine kwa dakika 15."]),
],

[
  'title' => 'Urge Surfing: Riding Out the Wave',
  'title_sw' => 'Kusafiri kwenye Wimbi la Hamu',
  'slug' => 'urge-surfing-gambling',
  'category' => 'gambling',
  'language' => 'en',
  'level' => 'intermediate',
  'duration_minutes' => 11,
  'thumbnail_emoji' => '🌊',
  'is_premium' => 1,
  'is_published' => 1,
  'order' => 3,
  'summary' => 'Use mindful observation to ride out gambling urges without acting on them, letting them rise, peak, and pass.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Tumia uchunguzi wa akili makini kupanda hamu ya kamari bila kutenda juu yake, kuziacha ziinuke, zifikilie kilele, na zipite.',
  'content' => "## What is urge surfing?\n\nUrge surfing is a mindfulness-based technique. Instead of fighting an urge or giving in to it, you observe it, watching it rise, peak, and pass, as a surfer rides a wave.\n\nThe key insight: urges are not permanent. They feel overwhelming in the moment but they have a beginning, a peak, and an end. Every urge you have ever had has eventually passed.\n\n## The technique\n\n**Step 1: Notice the urge is present.** Do not immediately try to suppress or satisfy it. Simply name it: there is the urge to bet.\n\n**Step 2: Observe where you feel it in your body.** Tightness in the chest? A specific feeling in your stomach? Restlessness in your hands or legs? Locate the sensation without judging it.\n\n**Step 3: Watch it like weather.** Imagine you are watching a storm from a safe window. The storm is real. You are not in it. Notice: it is getting stronger now. It seems to be at its peak. It is starting to ease.\n\n**Step 4: Breathe through it.** Use slow, extended breathing. Each exhale is a small act of not giving in.\n\n**Step 5: Remind yourself of the timeline.** Most urges peak within 10 to 20 minutes and reduce significantly within 30 minutes.\n\n## What makes this different from suppression\n\nSuppression increases urge intensity. Urge surfing does not ask you to suppress, only to observe. The urge is present. You are watching it. This psychological distance is the skill.\n\n## After the urge passes\n\nNote what happened. Write: how long did the peak last? How did it feel in your body? Over time, this log builds evidence that urges pass and that you can outlast them.",
  'content_sw' => "## Kusafiri kwenye wimbi la hamu ni nini?\n\nBadala ya kupigana na hamu au kutoa kwa, unaiangalia, ukiiona iinuke, ifikilie kilele, na ipite.\n\n## Mbinu\n\n1. Angalia hamu ipo, ipe jina\n2. Angalia inahisi wapi mwilini\n3. Iangalie kama hali ya hewa\n4. Pumua kupitia\n5. Jikumbusha: dakika 10-30",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Urges are not permanent. Every one has a beginning, peak, and end.", "Urge surfing means observing the urge, not suppressing or acting on it.", "Locate where you feel the urge physically and describe it.", "Watch it like weather from a safe window, present but not consuming you.", "Track your urge surfing: duration, intensity, physical sensation. Evidence builds over time."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Hamu si za kudumu, kila moja ina mwanzo, kilele, na mwisho.", "Kusafiri kwenye wimbi kunamaanisha kuangalia hamu, si kukandamiza wala kutenda.", "Fuatilia kusafiri kwako kwa hamu."]),
],

[
  'title' => 'Rebuilding Your Finances After Gambling',
  'title_sw' => 'Kujenga Tena Fedha Zako Baada ya Kamari',
  'slug' => 'rebuilding-finances-gambling',
  'category' => 'gambling',
  'language' => 'en',
  'level' => 'intermediate',
  'duration_minutes' => 14,
  'thumbnail_emoji' => '💰',
  'is_premium' => 1,
  'is_published' => 1,
  'order' => 4,
  'summary' => 'Practical steps to stabilise your finances, pay down gambling debts, and create barriers that protect your money during recovery.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Hatua za vitendo za kuimarisha fedha zako, kulipa madeni ya kamari, na kuunda vizuizi vinavyolinda pesa zako wakati wa kupona.',
  'content' => "## Why financial recovery matters\n\nFinancial damage from gambling is one of the main relapse triggers. Debt creates stress. Stress creates urges. Urges create more debt. Breaking this cycle requires addressing the financial damage directly.\n\n## Step 1: Get a clear picture\n\nWrite down every debt. Include SACCO loans, bank loans, money borrowed from family or friends, mobile loan apps such as Fuliza, Branch, or Tala, and any informal agreements. Add them up. The total is a number, not a judgment. Knowing the actual number is the beginning of addressing it.\n\n## Step 2: Protect your income immediately\n\nGive control of your income to a trusted person for a defined period of at least 3 to 6 months. Options include a trusted family member holding your card, salary paid directly to a joint account, or voluntary self-exclusion from mobile money platforms.\n\n## Step 3: Prioritise debts strategically\n\nFirst: mobile loan apps accruing daily interest. Second: any debt straining a relationship you need. Third: formal debts such as bank loans which typically have structured repayment options. Contact creditors early. Many will negotiate payment plans if you approach them before default.\n\n## Step 4: Create hard barriers to money\n\n- Delete all mobile betting apps permanently\n- Remove card details from betting websites\n- Set mobile money daily limits\n- Avoid carrying large amounts of cash in early recovery\n- Request self-exclusion from betting companies\n\n## Step 5: The small win principle\n\nOnce you have a repayment plan, track every debt paid off however small. Early in recovery, small financial wins matter. Your brain needs evidence that the damage is repairable.",
  'content_sw' => "## Kwa nini kupona kwa fedha ni muhimu\n\nUharibifu wa fedha kutokana na kamari ni moja ya visababishi vikuu vya kurudi.\n\n## Hatua muhimu\n\n1. Pata picha wazi ya deni lako lote\n2. Linda mapato yako mara moja kwa mtu unayemwamini\n3. Toa kipaumbele kwa madeni kwa mkakati\n4. Unda vizuizi vikali vya fedha\n5. Fuatilia malipo madogo ya deni kama ushindi mdogo",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Financial damage is a major relapse trigger. Address it directly as part of recovery.", "Write down every debt to the exact number. Clarity is the starting point.", "Give control of your income to a trusted person for 3 to 6 months during early recovery.", "Delete apps, remove saved cards, set mobile money limits. Create hard barriers.", "Track every debt payment as a small win. Your brain needs evidence that recovery is real."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Uharibifu wa fedha ni kisababishi kikuu cha kurudi, ushughulikie moja kwa moja.", "Andika kila deni hadi nambari halisi.", "Toa udhibiti wa mapato yako kwa mtu unayemwamini kwa miezi 3-6."]),
],

[
  'title' => 'Telling Someone About Your Gambling',
  'title_sw' => 'Kumwambia Mtu Kuhusu Kamari Yako',
  'slug' => 'telling-someone-gambling',
  'category' => 'gambling',
  'language' => 'en',
  'level' => 'advanced',
  'duration_minutes' => 13,
  'thumbnail_emoji' => '🤝',
  'is_premium' => 1,
  'is_published' => 1,
  'order' => 5,
  'summary' => 'Prepare for the disclosure conversation: who to tell, what to say, and how to handle their reaction.',
  'summary_sw' => 'Jiandae kwa mazungumzo ya ufafanuzi: nani wa kumwambia, nini cha kusema, na jinsi ya kushughulikia majibu yao.',
  'content' => "## Why disclosure matters\n\nResearch on addiction recovery consistently shows that people recover better with social support than alone. Secrecy around gambling feeds shame, and shame increases relapse risk. Telling even one person shifts the dynamic in important ways: it creates accountability, allows you to receive practical support, relieves the burden of hiding, and signals to yourself that recovery is real.\n\n## Who to tell first\n\nChoose someone who can hold difficult information without reacting in a way that will make things worse, who has a reason to care about your wellbeing, and who will not immediately tell everyone else without your permission. This does not have to be your closest person. It has to be the right person for this conversation.\n\n## Preparing for the conversation\n\n**Decide what you want from the conversation** before you talk. Are you looking for emotional support? Practical help managing finances? Just to have someone who knows?\n\n**Choose the setting.** Private, unrushed, when the other person is not stressed or distracted. Not by text.\n\n**A framework for what to say:** There is something I have been going through that I need to share with you. I have a problem with gambling. It has caused (brief description of impact). I am getting help and I am committed to stopping. What I need from you is (specific request).\n\n## Handling their reaction\n\n**Anger or hurt** are valid responses if they were affected. Do not defend in the moment. Acknowledge: I understand you are angry. You have reason to be. I am not asking you to trust me right now. I am asking for the chance to show you.\n\n**Shock or minimising** may feel dismissive. Hold your position: it has been affecting my life in ways I did not admit to anyone, including myself.\n\n**Relief** is also common. Many people say their loved ones had suspected something and were relieved to finally know.\n\n## If the first conversation goes badly\n\nThis does not mean disclosure was wrong. It means you may need to try with someone else, or give the person time to process.",
  'content_sw' => "## Kwa nini ufafanuzi unasaidia\n\nUtafiti unaonyesha kwamba watu wanapona vizuri zaidi na msaada wa kijamii kuliko peke yao. Siri kuhusu kamari inailisha aibu, na aibu huongeza hatari ya kurudi.\n\n## Jinsi ya kuandaa mazungumzo\n\nChagua mtu sahihi. Amua unachotaka kutoka kwa mazungumzo. Chagua mazingira ya faragha. Tumia mfumo: tatizo, athari, usaidizi unaohitajika.",
  'key_takeaways' => json_encode(["Secrecy feeds shame and shame increases relapse risk. Disclosure reduces both.", "Choose someone who can hold difficult information, not necessarily your closest person.", "Decide what you want from the conversation before it starts.", "Have a clear framework: the problem, the impact, that you are getting help, and a specific request.", "A difficult first reaction does not mean disclosure was wrong. They may need time."]),
  'key_takeaways_sw' => json_encode(["Siri inailisha aibu, aibu huongeza hatari ya kurudi.", "Chagua mtu anayeweza kushikilia habari ngumu.", "Amua unachotaka kutoka kwa mazungumzo kabla hawajaanza."]),
],

